**Project CRM Blueprint \-**

The next several pages are dedicated to providing a holistic and comprehensive overview of everything that a new CRM build with revolutionary agentic AI at its core can and should be able to do. 

Firstly, however, it is crucial to paint the picture and divulge exactly what the issues in the industry currently are. That is to say the significant gaps in the market which are costing estate agents and the property industry as a whole which being a fragmented industry \- tens of thousands of estate agents across the nation \- often lacks the concentrations of power and the necessary broad overview of the industry to take action and take advantage of paradigm shifts in technology. I want to change this and firmly believe that with the help of an excellent team of AI engineers a blueprint for this mission \- a living CRM \- can be built. 

It is important to understand how CRM‚Äôs and estate agencies are linked. Currently most CRM‚Äôs such as Alto Software (who manage 1 in 4 UK estate agents) are legacy systems whose only purpose is storing data. You can think of Alto as an old fashioned Argos catalogue where all the information crucial to the estate agent and collected and decades of business is held. This includes all the information about the properties of their clients about their diaries and appointments. The greatest strength of these legacy CRMs is a long history where they have cultivated trust from estate agents. However, paradoxically this has led to the opportunity worth discussing in this document and worth pulling off for the hackathon. 

Legacy CRMs are unable and unwilling to reinvent a successful product using AI; this would be too costly and too risky. What's more, the knowledge and detailed understanding of LLM‚Äôs and generative AI skews to a younger demographic of coders and AI engineers, many of whom are still in university\!\!

**Please see below the wholistic roadmap for everything a modern AI powered CRM should have based on my experience in the weeds of the industry;** 

There are six key areas that an estate agents CRM should focus on at the highest level these are as follows.

* Key business KPI‚Äôs drawn through the data inputted to the CRM  
* The front end of the lettings cycle   
* The back end of the lettings cycle  
* Property management  
* The front end of the sales cycle   
* The back end of the sales cycle

**Lets first discuss the Key KPI‚Äôs (key performance indicators) for any estate agent.**

The reason businesses use KPI‚Äôs is so that managers can get a clear picture of the health of their business \- what's working well and what potential improvements can be worked on. Generating KPI‚Äôs can be very time consuming and is often done in the industry via manually inputting raw data into separate spreadsheets. I envisage that through an intelligent CRM key data could be picked up and automatically organised into key easy to reference data points. 

**What are the Key KPI‚Äôs \-**

- Average Sales price per bedroom \- comparing also to the asking price as in what the average sales price achieved is and what percentage of the asking price this would represent. This is a vital KPI because by understanding the average prices achieved at a high level based on bedrooms estate agents can quickly and more reliably estimate potential values of new properties. Understanding how the achieved prices compare to the asking prices is crucial as this indicates which party has the power in the market. For instance in a buyers market where buyers have more influence we would expect the asking prices to be higher than the achieved prices whereas in a sellers market we would expect that asking or near asking price achieved prices could be maintained. Gauging who has the power in a market is important information for estate agents as this allows them to more easily manage the expectations of buyers and sellers.   
- Average let agreed price \- comparing also to the asking price as in what the average rent achieved is and what percentage of the asking price this would represent. This is a vital KPI because by understanding the average prices achieved at a high level based on bedrooms estate agents can quickly and more reliably estimate potential values of new properties. Understanding how the achieved prices compare to the asking prices is crucial as this indicates which party has the power in the market. For instance in a renters market where renters have more influence we would expect the asking prices to be higher than the achieved prices whereas in a landlords market we would expect that asking or near asking price achieved prices could be maintained. Gauging who has the power in a market is important information for estate agents as this allows them to more easily manage the expectations of renters and landlords.   
- Listing to sales ratio, with a detailed breakdown of why listings are lost. This is a crucial KPI because before earning any commission estate agents have to complete on properties and exchange or on the rental side have tenants move in. Quickly understanding what the conversion rate from the pipeline of available properties to sold or rented properties is important as this helps the agency understand roughly what percentage of their available stock will be turned to cash. For the sake of an example imagine an estate agent had 10 properties worth 1 million pounds each and charged a 1% fee. This would mean a pipeline worth ¬£100,000. If it was established that that agent had a conversion rate or a listing to sales ratio of 90% the manager of the branch could forecast an income of ¬£90,000 for the branch from the existing pipeline.   
- Days on the market, as mentioned, estate agents only get paid on successful completion of the transaction. This means that there is often a long tailwind between doing the work and getting paid; this can lead to cashflow problems. Understanding the time properties spend on the market helps directors and managers forecast and account for cashflow problems. 

- Fees generated \- through commissions (selling and letting properties) aswell as miscellaneous income through things like upselling cleaners a piechart showing monthly revenue would be the best way forward here.  
- Customer satisfaction \- this is a KPI for the property management team. Property management is a job that estate agents do primarily to keep business (margins are low) and the main indicator of success in property management is whether tenants and landlords feel happy with that estate agent. Typically customer feedback forms are sent out periodically (quarterly would be a good length of time) to landlords and tenants to gauge how happy tenants and landlord are and subtly find out if there are any issues with the ongoing service. The AI based CRM should do this automatically, reaching out to tenants and landlords and requesting their feedback. From the data collected here a temperature gauge can be built on the KPI indicator page in the CRM indicating how happy and satisfied customers are

**The front end of the lettings cycle** 

Each estate agent will organise the tasks to be completed differently, however, for the sake of our CRM and it‚Äôs UI the front end of the lettings cycle will refer to everything that is done between a landlord first deciding to instruct the estate agent to the offer from the prospective tenant being accepted. 

Lets dive into an overview of all the possible tasks that could be involved and where I trust AI can be embedded to improve the process. 

First we will go over the landlord's perspective and what the agent and subsequently the CRM needs to do here then we will go over what the tenants perspective is and what needs to be done on this side of the equation. 

The main ways a landlord reaches out to an estate agent are as follows \- through calling the office \- through a valuation request via email from one of the property portals or simply by walking into the office. It is my view that this stage of the process is not yet automatable through AI. This is because valuations are more tailored and situation specific than viewings. However, the CRM should be able to automatically provide the agent with a valuation pack.

### **Recommended Valuation and Price Range**

Based on the market analysis, we would suggest marketing the property within the following price range:

| Price Range |

Given the current Guide Price is ¬£195,000 (and has been reduced, suggesting it was likely initially marketed higher), this range supports the existing strategy but offers a clear upper limit.

### **Valuation Logic and Reasoning**

#### **1\. Comparable Property Analysis (Core Value)**

* **Baseline Value:** The strongest local comparable, Flat 6, Banister Court, sold for **¬£185,000** in April 2025\. This sets a firm base for the property's value on Court Road.  
* **Premium for En-Suite:** The subject property stands out by having **two bathrooms** (an en-suite plus a family bathroom), whereas many comparable flats in older blocks only have one. In the immediate area, the active comparables that also feature two bathrooms (Archers Road at ¬£215k, Hulse Road at ¬£210k) are asking for prices significantly higher than the Court Road baseline. This feature is highly desirable, especially for sharers or couples, and justifies a premium of ¬£10,000 \- ¬£15,000 over the ¬£185,000 baseline, placing the value around **¬£195,000 \- ¬£200,000**.  
* **Off-Road Parking:** The inclusion of an allocated off-road parking space is a major benefit in this central location and further enhances value.  
* **"Updated Flat" Status:** The listing mentions a "Spacious updated flat with new lease," indicating a good internal presentation and low maintenance for the buyer, supporting a value at the upper end of the local range.

#### **2\. Location and Infrastructure**

* **Train Station Proximity:** The property is excellently located for commuters, being approximately:  
  * **0.8 miles** to **Southampton Central Train Station**.  
  * **0.9 miles** to **St Denys Train Station**.  
  * This "walking distance" access to a major hub like Southampton Central is a key value driver in the SO15 postcode.  
* **Amenities and City Centre:** The flat is located within a 5-minute drive of the City Centre and is advertised as being "Walking Distance to Town Centre," which appeals strongly to first-time buyers, investors, and city workers.  
* **Schools:** The area benefits from local schools such as **Banister Primary School** and **Shirley Junior School** nearby, which maintains appeal for small families.

#### **3\. Market Conditions (UK/Southampton)**

* **Interest Rate Environment:** The current UK property market is sensitive to high interest rates, which typically dampen buyer demand and reduce bidding wars, particularly for flats that often attract first-time buyers relying on mortgages. This factor suggests that achieving a price significantly *over* the Guide Price may be challenging without exceptional demand.  
* **Local Market Trends:** While national data shows some pressure, the immediate area around Court Road has seen a steadying of prices. The properties in nearby buildings (Gwen Rhian Court) had an average value of ¬£156,763 as of August 2025, but the recent sale of a similar flat for ¬£185,000 (Apr 2025\) demonstrates that well-presented units are still achieving strong prices, especially those with modern features like the subject property's en-suite.  
* **Investor Appeal:** With strong rental growth predicted (average rental price in the area is around ¬£1,032 pcm), the property has high appeal for investors, which creates a second pool of motivated buyers and helps underpin the valuation.

#### **Conclusion**

The subject property is superior to the ¬£185,000 sold comparable due to its key advantage of having **two bathrooms** and good presentation. It competes directly with the asking prices of comparable 2-bedroom/2-bathroom units on Archers and Hill Lane, which are asking ¬£215,000-¬£220,000 but may be in more premium apartment blocks.

The estimated market price of **¬£195,000** is a fair and achievable target, aligning it with its original guide price and reflecting a reasonable premium for the en-suite and parking, while acknowledging the ¬£185,000 local sale baseline and current market caution. A motivated buyer or investor could push the price towards the upper range of **¬£205,000**.

Now we have built a way for landlords and properties to be registered and the data inputted to our CRM we need to look at the other aspect of the front end job of an estate agency. This is registering prospective tenants, commonly referred to as applicants and this will be how I refer to them in this document. 

The first stage of an applicant's life cycle is the initial conversation with the estate agent called the registration. This is where the key details are gathered so that the estate agent can best assist on the property search. The key here is to uncover as much data and information about the applicant as possible so that you can tailor your pitches (as the agent) and suggest the best possible properties for the applicant. The key here is to ask great questions, however, as almost all registration conversations are the same this presents our CRM an opportunity to step in and register applicants on the behalf of the estate agent through AI. Recording and transcribing the details of its conversations on the applicant tab saving the agents a huge amount of time and giving them a great first impression and collecting the key information to help their ongoing property search. Adding good and accurate relevant information to the CRM is key as more often than not the first property applicants enquire about does not end up being the property they move into so often estate agents have to show the same applicants multiple properties before that applicant finds the right home. 

Please see below the key applicant registration questions on the lettings side \- these are the same questions I asked applicants and that helped me let 12 properties in one month. 

What is your ideal move date?, why

Who will be living with you at the property?

Do you have any pets?

What budget were you looking up to?

How will you be funding the rent?

Are there any other key criteria or must haves for you in your new home \- things like a south facing garden, any schools you‚Äôd want to be near?

The automated response should cover and ask these questions automatically adding this to the CRM.

## **‚úÖ What leading CRMs do for Applicant/Prospective Tenant records**

Here are a few features from the market:

* Reapit describes the ‚ÄúApplicant Record‚Äù as ‚Äúall applicant info on single-screen ‚Ä¶ from marketing consent and key requirements to offers and applicant status. Easily match applicants with suitable properties.‚Äù [reapit.com+1](https://www.reapit.com/platform/sales-crm?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Jupix supports ‚ÄúProperty matching from the applicant screen ‚Ä¶ modify criteria, send matches to applicant‚Äù for both sales and lettings. [support.jupix.com+1](https://support.jupix.com/hc/en-gb/articles/360011815797-Property-matching-from-the-applicant-screen?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Alto offers ‚ÄúApplicant matching‚Äù in their Lettings CRM (smart match engine, match emails, quick search) and a portal where applicants book viewings and have some self-service. [Alto Software+1](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/alto-lettings-crm/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Many systems integrate communications (email/SMS), automatic matching, property sending, viewing scheduling and applicant status management.

## **So the CRM should cover all these core applicant workflows.**

## **üßÆ Comprehensive list of Applicant-Record fields & features (for lettings)**

### **A. Basic identity & contact**

1. Applicant ID (internal UUID)

2. Full name (title, first name, last name)

3. Date of birth

4. Contact numbers: mobile, landline

5. Email address(es)

6. Postal / correspondence address

10. Preferred language (if relevant)

### **B. Applicant status & lifecycle**

11. Applicant status (New ‚Üí Qualified ‚Üí Viewing Booked ‚Üí Offer Submitted ‚Üí References ‚Üí Let Agreed ‚Üí Tenancy Started / Archived)

12. Date of registration / first contact

13. Assigned agent or team member (owner)

14. Source of applicant (portal, website, referral, lead campaign)

15. Priority level (High / Medium / Low)

16. Pipeline or segment tag (e.g., ‚Äú2-bed student‚Äù, ‚Äúprofessional couple‚Äù, ‚Äúpet friendly‚Äù)

### **C. Property requirements / match criteria**

17. Type of property wanted (flat/house, furnished/unfurnished)

18. Desired number of bedrooms/bathrooms

19. Desired rent budget (minimum, preferred, maximum)

20. Preferred locations / postcodes / areas of interest

### **D. Matching & property notifications**

26. Property matches list (linked properties that fit criteria)

27. Match send history (when/which property details sent)

28. Applicant feedback on matches (accepted/declined, notes)

29. Viewing scheduling from applicant record (book viewing, send invites, reminders) ‚Äî Jupix supports this. [support.jupix.com+1](https://support.jupix.com/hc/en-gb/articles/4960772255775-Book-a-viewing-from-the-applicant-record?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

30. Quick search / ‚Äúfind matching properties‚Äù button using criteria.

### **E. Offers & tenancy progress (pre-tenancy)**

31. Offer submitted ‚Äì property, rent, term, conditions

32. Offer accepted date (if applicable)

33. Holding deposit paid (amount, date, status)

34. Reference status (tenant, guarantor) ‚Äì pass/fail/pending

35. Right to Rent check status & date

36. Move-in date agreed

37. Contract signing status

38. Tenancy record link (when moved in)

### **F. Documents & attachments**

39. Proof of ID uploaded (passport/driving licence)

40. Proof of address uploaded (utility bill, bank statement)

41. Reference/credit check documents

42. Guarantor details & documents (if applicable)

43. Agreement/contract documents (draft, final)

44. Uploaded other documents (pets agreement, inventory receipt)

45. Document expiry or review dates (if applicable)

### **G. Communication & activity tracking**

46. Notes field (internal agent notes: e.g., "prefers Saturday viewings")

47. Activity feed: calls logged, emails sent, SMS messages, tasks created

48. Viewing feedback entered (by agent after viewing)

49. Email/SMS templates used / repeated tasks (e.g., ‚Äúsend new matches‚Äù mail)

50. Portal invitation status (if applicant has login to applicant portal) ‚Äî Alto‚Äôs Applicant Portal supports it. [support.altosoftware.co.uk](https://support.altosoftware.co.uk/hc/en-gb/articles/5048169919519-PropertyFile-Applicant-Portal?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

### **H. Marketing & analytics metadata**

51. Date last matched / date last contacted

52. Number of properties sent in last 30/60/90 days

53. Number of viewings attended / offers made / offers accepted

### **I. Compliance & flags**

## **üß≠ Workflow & UI features (for developers/designers)**

* Single-view Applicant Record screen, combining all the above into a clear page with tabs or collapsible cards: ‚ÄúOverview‚Äù, ‚ÄúRequirements‚Äù, ‚ÄúMatches & Viewings‚Äù, ‚ÄúOffers & References‚Äù, ‚ÄúDocuments‚Äù, ‚ÄúActivity‚Äù.

* Quick action buttons: ‚ÄúAdd Property Match‚Äù, ‚ÄúSend Matches‚Äù, ‚ÄúBook Viewing‚Äù, ‚ÄúUpload Documents‚Äù, ‚ÄúStart Reference‚Äù, ‚ÄúMove to Let Agreed‚Äù.

* Matching engine widget: the applicant record shows ‚ÄúSuggested Properties‚Äù list live, with ability to filter/modify criteria and send to applicant. Jupix supports ‚ÄúRun Property Match‚Äù from applicant screen

* Portal for applicant (self-service): allow applicant to log in, update requirements, see viewings, accept matches. Alto‚Äôs Applicant Portal does this.

* Automated reminders / tasks: e.g., send new matches weekly, send follow-up after viewing, notify agent when reference fails or due.

* Consent & marketing flags visible prominently.

* Analytics snapshot: display key applicant metrics (viewings booked, offers made, status).

* Mobile friendly: applicants may update availability via mobile, agent can view on mobile.

* Integration: referencing partner API (Alto integrates with multiple reference partners).

## **üéØ Key differences compared to Property & Landlord modules**

* Applicant data is **demand side** (tenant) rather than supply side (property/landlord). So emphasis is on requirements, matching, status progression, offers, references ‚Äî whereas properties emphasise attributes, compliance, rent, documents, landlord emphasises ownership & bank details.

* The applicant workflow is shorter and more dynamic: registration ‚Üí matching ‚Üí viewing ‚Üí offer ‚Üí reference ‚Üí tenancy.

* Matching engine and communication workflows are more important on applicant side.

* Consent/marketing and preference data are more critical for applicants (GDPR, property alerts).

* Viewings scheduling and feedback loops are heavily applicant-centric.

* Status tracking matters: you‚Äôll want to easily see where in the pipeline each applicant is (e.g., ‚ÄúWaiting references‚Äù, ‚ÄúOffer accepted‚Äù, ‚ÄúTenancy started‚Äù).

This is what we should work towards when building the UI for the applicants side.

We have now peaced together the entire process of the front end of lettings. Except for the necessity of the CRM to send out matches. As mentioned earlier good registration is key because more often than not applicants need to go to multiple viewings before deciding on a property. This creates a need for estate agents to be constantly following up on applicants. For instance as a negotiator I used to spend one day a week calling through applicants and one morning a week sending out ‚Äúproperty match‚Äù emails to my applicants. This represents about 15-20% of my time as an estate agent and the CRM should be capable of sending matches automatically using AI. Either through phone calls emails or whatsapp. The matches should be personalised and should use the information gathered in the registration phase to hook the applicants. For instance if the applicant mentions they have a dog named fluffy the AI matching agent should automatically reach out and send a personal note inside the match saying something like I think Fluffy would love this 80 foot south facing back garden. The more personal the match the more likely the agent is to engage the applicant. This is why data on the properties and data on the applicants is SO important and we need the applicant and property cards to store a lot of key information. Matches should be sent at timed intervals. I liked to do them once a week\!

**The Back End of the Lettings Cycle \-** 

The back end of the lettings cycle refers to everything that happens once the offer is accepted. This means we go from a property to let to a property let be all the way to potentially a managed property. The applicant meanwhile transitions from a prospective tenant to a tenant.

Here is a detailed break down of the steps involved in the lettings progression stage,

| 1.1 | Log Offer Details to CRM | Update Applicant Record (E) with: Property ID, Agreed Rent, Tenancy Term, Proposed Start Date, and any Special Conditions (e.g., Pet Clause). | Records the key commercial terms. |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **1.2** | **Log Offer as Accepted** | Change **Applicant Status (B)** to "Offer Accepted." Change **Property Status** to "Let by" | Triggers the start of the progression timeline. |
| **1.3** | **Mark Property as Let Agreed** | Change **Property Status** to **"Let Agreed."** This should automatically push an update to portals (Rightmove/Zoopla) to show the property is no longer available. | Ensures property is taken off the market. |
| **1.4** | **Collect & Track Holding Deposit** | **Log Holding Deposit Paid (E):** Amount, Date Paid, Payment Method. **Finance Module:** Create a deposit liability record. | Complies with the Tenant Fees Act 2019\. The property is formally reserved. |
| **1.5** | **Send Offer Confirmation Emails** | **Activity Feed (G):** Log sent emails. **Email Templates (G):** Use templates to send formal confirmation to the Tenant and the Landlord. | Sets expectations, confirms agreement, and outlines next steps (referencing/deposit deduction terms). |
| **1.6** | **Generate Pre-Tenancy Statement** | **Finance Module:** Auto-calculate the remaining balance due before move-in (First Month's Rent \+ Security Deposit \- Holding Deposit). | Provides tenants with a clear financial roadmap. |

### **2\. Referencing and Compliance (The "Verification" Stage)**

| \# | Action/Task | CRM Function/Data Field | Compliance/Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **2.1** | **Start Referencing Process** | **Quick Action Button (Jupix/Alto style):** "Start Referencing." **Integration:** API call to referencing partner (e.g., Goodlord) to send applicant data. | Outsourced verification of income, employment, and credit history. |
| **2.2** | **Track Reference Status** | **Reference Status Field (E):** Updated automatically via API/Manually (Pending $\\rightarrow$ Pass $\\rightarrow$ Fail / Pass with Conditions). | Ensures all tenants meet the financial and background criteria. |
| **2.3** | **Right to Rent Check** | **Right to Rent Status Field (E):** Status and date verified. **Document Storage (F):** Store copies of ID/visas. | **MANDATORY UK LEGAL COMPLIANCE.** Failure to check leads to fines. |
| **2.4** | **Store Referencing Documents** | **Document Storage (F):** Upload: Applicant IDs (Passport/Driving Licence), Proof of Address, Full Referencing Report (e.g., Goodlord PDF). | Evidential compliance for audits and dispute resolution. |
| **2.5** | **AML/Guardianship Flags Check** | **Compliance Flags (I):** Confirm no Anti-Money Laundering flags (if required) or safeguarding issues. | Ensures legal and ethical standards are met. |

### **3\. Tenancy Documentation and Final Finances**

| \# | Action/Task | CRM Function/Data Field | Compliance/Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **3.1** | **Draft Tenancy Agreement (AST)** | **Document Drafting Module:** Auto-populate AST template using data from the Applicant Record (1.1). | Creates the legally binding contract. |
| **3.2** | **Send Statutory Documents to Tenant** | **Document History (G):** Log confirmed delivery of: **How to Rent Guide** (mandatory) and Energy Performance Certificate (EPC). | **MANDATORY UK LEGAL COMPLIANCE.** Must be provided *before* tenancy starts. |
| **3.3** | **Collect Remaining Move-in Monies** | **Finance Module:** Send automated payment request for the balance (1.6). **Status Update:** "Full Move-In Monies Received." | Ensures all rent/deposit is cleared before handing over keys. |
| **3.4** | **Register Security Deposit** | **Finance Module/Integration:** Transfer security deposit funds to a scheme (DPS, TDS) and issue the **Prescribed Information (PI)** to the tenant. | **MANDATORY UK LEGAL COMPLIANCE.** Must be done within 30 days of receipt. |
| **3.5** | **Sign Tenancy Agreement** | **Document Signing Module:** Send draft to all parties (Tenants, Landlord/Agent) for electronic signature. **Document Storage (F):** Store the final signed contract. | Formalizes the agreement. |

### **4\. Logistics & Move-In Preparation**

| \# | Action/Task | CRM Function/Data Field | Compliance/Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **4.1** | **Arrange Professional Clean** | **Task Creation (G):** Book and log clean with preferred supplier. | Ensures the property is fit for a new tenancy (standard industry practice). |
| **4.2** | **Arrange Inventory Check-in** | **Task Creation (G):** Book and log inventory clerk for check-in on move-in day. **Document Storage (F):** Upload final inventory report. | Essential legal evidence for the deposit dispute process. |
| **4.3** | **Utility & Council Tax Notification** | **Quick Action:** "Notify Utilities." Generate automated emails/API transfers to the Council, water, gas, and electricity providers with move-in dates and new tenant names. | **MANDATORY AGENCY TASK.** Ensures smooth transition of bills and accurate billing. |
| **4.4** | **Key Update/Arrangement** | **Property Record:** Update Key Codes/Access Notes. **Task:** Arrange for keys to be cut and ready for collection/handover. | Logistical essential. |
| **4.5** | **Final Progression Check** | **Automated Checklist:** A system checklist must be 100% complete before the **"Move-In"** button can be clicked. | Guards against compliance failures (e.g., ensuring PI and How to Rent Guide are sent). |

### **5\. Move-In Day & Transition to Management**

| \# | Action/Task | CRM Function/Data Field | Compliance/Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **5.1** | **Execute Move-In** | **Quick Action Button:** **"Move-In/Tenancy Start."** This is the final step. | Formal start of the legal tenancy. |
| **5.2** | **Create Tenancy Record** | **Automated Action:** The CRM must archive the Applicant Record and generate a new **Active Tenancy Record** with all inherited data (rent, term, tenant names). | Essential for rent collection and property management. |
| **5.3** | **Set Property to Managed Status** | **Property Record:** Status updated to **"Tenanted \- Fully Managed"** (or appropriate management level). **Assigned Agent (B):** Owner changed from Lettings Negotiator to Property Manager. | Transition of responsibility to the property management team. |
| **5.4** | **Schedule First Rent & Management Tasks** | **Finance/Task Module:** Schedule the first rent payment and set up management tasks (e.g., mid-term inspection in 3 months). | Ensures immediate start of the management cycle. |

**Property Management Aspect \-** 

Property management refers to everything that happens after the new tenant/s move in to the day that they leave. Property management is a job often insulated from technological change, however, I believe this is the aspect of estate agency that we can most heavily disrupt using AI. 

Please see below a list of all the jobs done by property managers, they are stratified into 

### **I. Financial Management & Rent Control**

| **Arrears Management** | Identify late payments, log communications (calls/emails), issue formal Late Rent/Arrears notices (automated generation). | **Arrears Workflow:** Automated task generation on missed payment; standardised arrears letter templates. |
| **Landlord Payments** | Process and remit monthly rental income to the landlord, deducting management fees, maintenance costs, and other charges. | **Finance/Landlord Statements:** Automated calculation of net rent; generation of detailed monthly Landlord Statements. |
| **Invoicing & Fees** | Raise and track invoices for management fees, renewal fees, and ad-hoc charges (e.g., call-out fees). | **Invoicing & Billing:** Tracking fee agreements against properties; automated invoice generation. |
| **Financial Reporting** | Produce end-of-year or quarterly financial summaries for the landlord for tax purposes. | **Reporting/Analytics:** Financial reports module with income/expense breakdown \- generated automatically and quarterly |

Triage urgency (Emergency/Urgent/Routine). | **Maintenance Portal/Job Tracking:** Centralized logging; status pipeline (New $\\rightarrow$ Quoted $\\rightarrow$ Assigned $\\rightarrow$ Complete); urgency flags. |

An AI could pick up out of hours calls and contact the emergency contractor to explain the problem? |

**Let‚Äôs look into the sales process** 

**Sales Front End**

The process for the front end of sales is fortunately relatively similar to the front end of lettings. This is to say that in principle all of the key events map almost perfectly. Largely the only difference is in the terminologies used. For example landlords are vendors and applicants refers now to buyers not tenants. 

The front end of the sales process starts with the vendor/seller side. The first step here is that the prospective vendor will contact the estate agent to discuss a property they would like to put onto the market; this will lead to a valuation of the property. Our CRM should be able to automatically create valuation packs on the behalf of estate agents pulling together information found online and details about prices achieved for comparable properties held by the estate agent. The valuation pack should be detailed and explain briefly the current market situation based on our KPI‚Äôs and provide a range of potential prices suggesting a price at which the property should go quickly and the price which a vendor may be able to hold out for. The valuation pack should be easy to interpret and include suggestions on things the vendor could do to influence the price.

**Recommended Valuation and Price Range**  
 Based on the market analysis above, we suggest marketing the property in the following range:

| Price Range | Strategy |
| ----- | ----- |
| **¬£205,000 \- ¬£215,000** | Quick-sale price band ‚Äî fair value to generate strong enquiry and faster exchange. |
| **¬£220,000 (Guide Price)** | Balanced pricing: aligns with active market and allows room for negotiation; realistic for the property given its features. |
| **¬£240,000 \- ¬£250,000+** | Aspirational price band ‚Äî achievable only if the property is in **excellent** condition, larger size (above average for the block), lease length favourable, low charges and exemplary presentation. |

**Valuation Logic and Reasoning**

1. **Comparable Property Analysis (Core Value)**

   * The strongest recent transaction: 6 Moore Close at ¬£210k (Jan-24). This provides a solid foundation for value.

   * Units of similar size/spec in the same development achieved ¬£247k-¬£260k in 2022 ‚Äî indicating upside for premium units.

   * Active listings at ¬£220k-¬£235k signify current market appetite.

2. **Premium for Two Bathrooms & Condition**

   * The subject property‚Äôs second bathroom/en-suite adds a premium relative to many flats in older blocks with one bath.

   * Allocated parking \+ modern build (2017) boost appeal and value.

3. **Location & Infrastructure**

   * Moore Close (Banister Park) is highly accessible: walking distance to city centre, good transport, leisure amenities and Southampton Common ‚Äî strong locational datapoint.

   * Newer build, low maintenance appeal vs older stock in SO15.

4. **Market Conditions**

   * Flat/apartment markets are generally more sensitive to interest-rates and mortgage availability compared to houses ‚Äî while demand remains, buyer caution can affect top bands.

   * Given the flat is in a strong micro-location, the recommended guide centre price (¬£220k) is realistic.

---

**Conclusion**  
 The subject property is **slightly superior** to the benchmark ¬£210k sale due to its two-bathrooms, modern build and parking. A marketing strategy centred around **¬£220,000** gives a realistic target with the potential to achieve offers in the **¬£210k-¬£235k** band if presentation is strong. Should the property meet all top-unit criteria (larger size, excellent condition, favourable lease & charges) then the **¬£240k-¬£250k+** range becomes plausible.

Much like at the front end of the lettings process. It is often the case that applicants need multiple viewings before deciding and finalising on a property. To be a successful sales agent you need to therefore understand what your buyers are looking for. This means registration is crucial and asking the right questions to understand your buyers needs is a vital job which the CRM can and should automate in a similar fashion. Here are some key buyer registration questions that can help estate agents learn about their clients and find more people the right properties faster.

Have you got an ideal timeframe for moving? 

What's prompting the move?

What price are you looking up to?

What condition are you looking for done up or are you willing to take on more of a project?

What tenure are you looking for, leaseholds or freeholds?

Have you got a property to sell before buying?

If yes then is your current property already on the market or under offer?

Are you a first time buyer?

Have you got a mortgage in principle or will this be a cash purchase?

Are there any other key criteria such as being near certain schools or parking?

Correctly implementing an automated call back agent for the sales side would be very impressive \- this is often more technical than the registration of tenants because there are more technicalities like how the property will be paid for if there will be a chain etc that these questions try to get to the bottom of. 

The details of the phone call should be automatically transcribed to the CRM. And used to send automatic matches to that applicant.

Sending automatic property matches is important as this is a huge time drain on estate agents. A big part of the job is making people aware of properties coming onto the market and drumming up interest to arrange viewings and open houses which get stock sold\! 

Currently much like letting agents estate agents on the sales side spend hours matching properties each week manually sending emails manually dialling potential clients. This should all be automated and clients should be reached out automatically and personally via email and text with the potential for viewings being booked in automatically based on negotiators availability. 

Automatic property matches should be personalised to the specific applicant based off of the registration questions such as if the applicant mentions on registration that they are a young family the automatic email/text should mention something like Only a 5 minute walk to X primary school\!\! (should this be true of course).

In terms of producing the applicant card where the data and information for the prospective buyer is stored the information that is required to be easily accessed/inputted is as follows.

## **TOP-LEVEL OBJECTS & RELATIONSHIPS**

* **Buyer (primary object)** ‚Äî main record

* **Contacts** ‚Äî allow linked contacts (partner, financial contact, solicitor, broker)

* **Linked Properties** ‚Äî matched properties, previously viewed properties, saved favourites

* **Offers** ‚Äî list of offers made by this buyer (linked)

* **Viewings** ‚Äî scheduled and completed viewings

* **Documents** ‚Äî uploads (AIP, Proof of Funds, ID)

* **Activity Log** ‚Äî calls, emails, notes, tasks

* **Pipeline / Sales Stage** ‚Äî e.g., Registered ‚Üí Viewing ‚Üí Interested ‚Üí Offer ‚Üí Offer Accepted ‚Üí Exchanged ‚Üí Completed

* **Alerts / Saved Searches** ‚Äî user-configurable criteria and alerts per buyer (matching engine)  
   (These relationships are standard in purpose-built CRMs and implied by features in Reapit/Alto/Jupix). [reapit.com+1](https://www.reapit.com/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

---

## **1\) CORE IDENTIFIERS & ADMIN**

* **Buyer ID** ‚Äî system auto-generated (string) ‚Äì unique.

* **Record created / last updated / created by / last updated by** ‚Äî timestamps & user IDs (audit).

* **Status / Stage** ‚Äî enum: Registered, Active, Dormant, Hot/Warm/Cold, Archived.

* **Source** ‚Äî enum/text: Portal (Rightmove/Zoopla), Branch Walk-In, Referral, Social, Advertising (store lead source).

  * *Why*: Conversion analytics & lead source ROI.

* **Tags / Labels** ‚Äî free tags for segmentation (e.g., ‚ÄúFirst-time buyer‚Äù, ‚ÄúInvestor‚Äù, ‚ÄúRelocation‚Äù).  
   *Dev note:* index tags for fast search.

---

## **2\) CONTACT & IDENTITY**

* **Primary contact name** (first / last) ‚Äî required.

* **Title / Preferred name** ‚Äî optional.

* **Alternate contacts** ‚Äî partner, parent, guarantor (each as contact sub-record with relationship type).

* **Phone(s)** ‚Äî primary, mobile, secondary (with call/SMS capability).

* **Email(s)** ‚Äî primary, secondary (validated).

* **Preferred contact method & time** ‚Äî enum.

* **Current correspondence address** ‚Äî with postcode lookup (autocomplete).

* **Current property status** ‚Äî Renting / Owner / Living with family / Vacant (helps chain logic).

* **Nationality / DOB (optional, for AML/identity)** ‚Äî only if required and with privacy handling.

**Why**: basic contacting, AML and chain assessment.

## **3\) FINANCIAL & AFFORDABILITY (CRITICAL)**

* **Proof of Funds** ‚Äî upload(s), type (savings/sale/gift), amount, verified boolean and verifier.

* **Deposit source** ‚Äî savings / sale of property / equity release / gift (string).

* **Monthly household income** ‚Äî number (optional) and employment status.

* **Mortgage broker details** ‚Äî link to broker contact (name, firm, phone, email).

* **Affordability notes** ‚Äî text (any special financial arrangements).

* **AML / KYC status** ‚Äî enum: Not checked / In progress / Verified / Failed; link to verification provider result (Thirdfort, Credas, etc.).

  * *Why:* Reapit and other CRMs emphasise AML & verification workflows; capture result and date. [reapit.com](https://www.reapit.com/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

**Validation / UX:** require either AIP or Proof of Funds for ‚ÄúHot‚Äù buyer classification. Allow document expiry reminders (AIP expires).

---

## **4\) BUYER STATUS & READINESS**

* **Buying Timeline / Desired Move Date** ‚Äî date or relative text (ASAP / 1‚Äì3 months / 3‚Äì6 months / 6+ months).

* **Readiness level** ‚Äî Hot / Warm / Cold (agent-assigned).

* **Has property to sell?** ‚Äî boolean \+ link to vendor property record if same agency.

* **Is there a chain?** ‚Äî text description / chain id (link).

## **5\) SEARCH CRITERIA (structured & searchable)**

* **Primary Locations (list)** ‚Äî each with radius (e.g., Southampton, 2 miles).

* **Secondary Areas** ‚Äî list.

* **Property Type** ‚Äî Flat / Terraced / Semi / Detached / Bungalow / New Build / Conversion.

* **Age / Condition Preference** ‚Äî New build / Modern / Period / Renovation acceptable.

* **Key Features required** ‚Äî checkboxes: Ensuite, Energy performance, EPC rating, Home office, Open-plan kitchen, Floorplan size, Garage.

**Why**: drives matching / saved search engine and alerts (many CRMs include matching features). [reapit.com+1](https://www.reapit.com/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

## **6\) MATCHING & ALERTS**

* **Saved searches** ‚Äî saved filter criteria \+ name \+ last-run timestamp.

**Why**: automated lead-to-property matching is core CRM functionality (Reapit & Alto emphasise prospecting & matching tools). [Alto Software+1](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/product-features/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

## **7\) VIEWINGS & INTERACTIONS**

* **Viewing availability** ‚Äî days/times (structured).

## **8\) OFFERS & NEGOTIATION**

* **Offers made** ‚Äî table with property id, offer amount, date, conditions (subject to), expiry, status (pending/accepted/rejected).

* **Offer source** ‚Äî direct / via broker / online portal.

---

## **9\) DOCUMENTS & UPLOADS (DOCUMENT MANAGEMENT)**

* **Identity docs** ‚Äî passport / driving licence (uploads with expiry metadata).

* **Proof of funds / bank statements** ‚Äî uploads \+ verified flag.

* **Proof of address** ‚Äî utility/council tax (uploads).

---

## **10\) COMMUNICATIONS & ACTIVITY**

* **Activity timeline** ‚Äî chronological feed (calls, emails, SMS, notes). Auto-log email threads and integrate with calendar.

* **Templates used** ‚Äî record which email templates have been sent (valuation, follow-up, legal info).

* **Agent assignments** ‚Äî primary agent, negotiator, viewing agent.

* **Tasks & Reminders** ‚Äî follow-ups, AIP expiry checks, viewing confirmations.

**Why**: visibility and auditability of all contact, and automation of follow-ups (common in Alto & Reapit). [Alto Software+1](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/product-features/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

---

## **11\) GDPR / CONSENTS / PERMISSIONS**

* **Marketing consents** ‚Äî email/sms/phone (with timestamp & method of collection).

* **Third-party sharing consent** ‚Äî boolean \+ timestamp.

* **Data retention expiry** ‚Äî auto-calc based on consent/policy.

* **Right to Erasure / Data Access requests** ‚Äî logged with status.

**Why**: legal requirement; provide UI to capture and display consent for agents. (Reapit docs emphasise compliance features.) [reapit.com](https://www.reapit.com/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

## **12\) REPORTING / KPIs ON THE CARD**

* **Buyer score / likelihood to convert** ‚Äî composite score (AIP, readiness, viewing count).

* **Time registered** ‚Äî days since registration.

* **Number of viewings / offers / matches** ‚Äî quick stats.

   (Useful for dashboards and prioritisation features.)

## **13\) BACKEND / TECH & INTEGRATION NOTES (for developers)**

* **APIs & Portal Feeds:** store portal reference IDs (Rightmove, Zoopla) for any leads & link to listing IDs. (Alto/others provide portal integration.) [Alto Software](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/product-features/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* **Webhooks:** push new property matches & viewings to buyer notifications.

* **Document store:** S3-style file store with metadata (type, uploadedBy, verifiedBy, expiry).

* **Search & Filters:** full-text search on notes \+ indexed fields for location, budget, tags.

* **Custom fields:** allow agency-specific fields; store as key/value pairs.

* **Security:** encrypt PII at rest, RBAC for sensitive docs, audit logging for all edits.

* **AML Integration:** option to call external AML providers and persist results (Reapit/Alto integrations are common). [reapit.com+1](https://www.reapit.com/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

## **14\) UI / UX Recommendations (developer-friendly)**

* **Tabbed form**: Buyer Details / Financials / Search Criteria / Viewings / Offers / Documents / Activity / GDPR. (Matches modern CRM UI patterns used by Alto/Reapit.) [Alto Software+1](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/product-features/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* **Smart validation**: e.g., if buyer says ‚Äúcash‚Äù then AIP not required but Proof of Funds required.

* **Inline tooltips**: explain why each financial field is asked (for non-agent developers to understand context).

## **15\) Example Minimal Required Fields to Record at Registration (quick checklist)**

1. Full name, primary phone, primary email (contact)

2. Budget range and max price (affordability)

3. Buying position (AIP/cash/needs mortgage)

4. Desired locations and property type (search criteria)

5. Intended move date (timing)

6. Has property to sell? (chain)

7. Preferred contact method / viewing availability

8. Consent to contact (GDPR)

9. Source (portal/referral)

10. Assigned agent (internal)

These are the minimum required to have a functional buyer record and begin automated matching and outreach.

Now we have covered the front end of sales we need to have systems in place to manage the back end of the sales process. This involves everything from the stage at which the offer is accepted to the stage at which contracts are exchanged. This is one of the most technically challenging parts of estate agency because emotions are high fall throughs are up to 20% of properties and the process is often long drawn out and complex with long chains and lots of independent parties weighing in on the deal trying to renegotiate etc. 

The job of sales progression is often managed by dedicated sales progressors and it is my view that this process is harder to automate because the number of edge cases likely exceeds any standards. 

Please see a comprehensive list of the back end sales process and what the CRM should do to track this process (at this fiddly stage of the process the CRMs main job should be as a virtual check list and reminding agent.).

The sales process should be tracked like a timeline here is how the timeline looks,

## **Sales Progression Workflow & CRM Field/Task Specification**

**Stage** ‚Üí **Trigger / Key Actions** ‚Üí **CRM Tasks/Fields to Track**

### **1\. Offer Accepted ‚Üí Mark as SSTC (Sold Subject to Contract)**

* Trigger: Offer accepted by vendor & buyer; property status changes to SSTC.

* CRM must update: Property Status field \= ‚ÄúSSTC‚Äù.

* Tasks/Fields:

  * Offer ID, Date accepted, Offer amount, Buyer & Vendor contact linked.

  * Assign ‚ÄúSales Progressor / Case Handler‚Äù (field: SalesProgressor).

  * Task: Intro call to buyer & vendor (auto-trigger).

  * Chain Flag: Link to ‚ÄúSale Chain‚Äù record (if multi-link).

  * Chain\_View: Dashboard or chain-view panel (Reapit supports chain view in their ‚ÄúSales Progression Dashboard‚Äù feature). [reapit.com](https://www.reapit.com/content-hub/elevate-24-release-building-the-future-of-reapit-technology?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

### **2\. Sales Memorandum / Instruction to Solicitor**

* Action: Generate & send sales memorandum (agent ‚Üí solicitor/vendor).

* CRM must allow: Generation of Memorandum document (template) \+ upload field.

* Fields: Solicitor (Buyer side), Solicitor (Vendor side), Solicitor Contact Info.

* Task: Send memorandum to solicitor and confirm acceptance.

### **3\. Key Documents Requested from Vendor**

* Action: Request from vendor: Title (freehold/leasehold), Management Pack, TA6/TA7, TA10, Service Charges, etc.

* CRM fields/tasks:

  * Upload fields: TitleDocument, ManagementPack, TA6, TA7, TA10.

  * Leasehold vs Freehold flag.

  * ServiceChargeAnnual, GroundRent (if leasehold).

  * Task: Vendor to supply documents by X date.

  * Document status field: Not received / Received / Verified.

### **4\. Buyer Mortgage & Survey Progress**

* Action: Confirm buyer‚Äôs mortgage is in progress; survey arranged.

* Fields/tasks:

  * BuyerMortgageStatus: AIP / In progress / Offered / Approved.

  * SurveyOrdered: boolean \+ date ordered \+ surveyor name.

  * SurveyReportReceived: boolean \+ date.

  * Survey Issues Flag: Yes/No \+ Notes about any renegotiation.

  * Task: Monitor mortgage progress by date.

  * Automation: If mortgage not approved by X week ‚Üí alert.

### **5\. Searches & Management Pack Info (if Leasehold)**

* Action: Order local authority searches; review management pack (for flats).

* Fields/tasks:

  * SearchesOrdered: Date.

  * SearchesClear: boolean \+ date cleared.

  * ManagementPackReviewed: boolean \+ date.

  * ServiceChargeHistory: numeric field(s).

  * Flag: Major works planned? Yes/No \+ Details (important for mortgage).

  * Task: Review searches and management pack within set timeframe.

### **6\. Exchange Preparation**

* Action: Check all parties happy, mortgage approved, searches clear, vendor obligations done.

* CRM must update: Property Status \= ‚ÄúExchanged‚Äù.

* Fields/tasks:

  * ExchangeDate (planned).

  * MortgageOfferDate.

  * VendorsLegalObligationsComplete: boolean.

  * BuyersLegalObligationsComplete: boolean.

  * Task: Notify all parties of exchange date.

  * Document: Exchange contract uploaded (optional).

### **7\. Completion & Handover**

* Action: Book completion date, arrange funds, key handover, update status to ‚ÄúCompleted‚Äù.

* CRM tasks/fields:

  * CompletionDate.

  * FundsTransferred: boolean \+ date.

  * KeyHandoverDate/Time.

  * BuyerContact (link).

  * VendorContact (link).

  * PropertyStatus \= ‚ÄúCompleted‚Äù.

  * Task: Issue completion letter (template).

  * Task: Ask for review/testimonial from buyer and vendor.

### **8\. Post-Completion & Review**

* Action: Wrap-up: record testimonial, update referral database, archive chain.

* CRM fields/tasks:

  * ReviewRequested: boolean \+ date.

  * ReviewReceived: boolean \+ date \+ rating.

  * ReferralPotential: boolean \+ notes.

  * ArchiveDate: date when record will move to archive.

  * Chain analytics: record deal time, vendor/buyer satisfaction scores.

  * Task: Send ‚Äúwelcome pack‚Äù to buyer (optional).

## **Additional Columns / Data to Track (besides your original timeline)**

* Chain ID: for multi-link chains (Alto allows chain tracking & chain view). [Alto Software](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/product-features/property-sales-progression-for-estate-agents/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Progression Stage: numeric or descriptive e.g., 1=Offer, 2=SSTC, 3=Solicitor Instructed, 4=Searches, 5=Exchange, 6=Completion.

* Days in Stage: auto-calculated (=current date minus date stage started) ‚Äî helpful for alerts.

* Delay Reason: text/dropdown ‚Äî if the sale stalls, record reason (survey issues, finance delay, chain collapse).

* Assigned Team/Person: Field for which progressor is handling (important for multi-branch).

* Documents Pending Count: Integer of how many required docs still outstanding.

* Alerts/Notifications: Trigger system for upcoming deadlines (mortgage expiry, search expiry, vendor docs missing).

* Client Portal Access: Set flag if buyer/vendor portal is enabled (Alto‚Äôs ‚ÄúPropertyFile‚Äù portal allows real-time updates). [Alto Software](https://www.altosoftware.co.uk/product-features/property-sales-progression-for-estate-agents/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

* Communication History: store all emails, calls and texts linked to the transaction (audit trail).

* Mortgage/Finance Conditions: Free text for any special conditions (remortgage, bridging loan).

* Chain Lead Time Estimate: Forecast date of exchange/completion (for internal reporting).

* KPI Metrics: e.g., days from SSTC to Exchange, days from Exchange to Completion ‚Äî for agency reporting.

## **Suggested UI / Workflow for Developers**

* Use a **‚ÄúSales Progression‚Äù tab** on property record.

* Display a **progress bar or timeline** at top showing stages and their status (Offer ‚Üí SSTC ‚Üí Solicitor Instructed ‚Üí Searches ‚Üí Exchange ‚Üí Completion).

* Beside timeline display: key dates (Offer Date, SSTC Date, Exchange Date, Completion Date).

* Below: **Checklist component** showing required tasks/documents (vendor packs, mortgage, searches) with status icons (‚úÖ/üî¥).

* Right-hand panel: ‚ÄúChain View‚Äù listing all linked transactions (vendor chain, buyer‚Äôs purchase, etc).

* Notifications/Alerts: Pop-up or dashboard tile for any items overdue (e.g., ‚ÄúManagement pack pending‚Äù, ‚ÄúSearches not ordered‚Äù).

* Client Portal toggle: when enabled, send status updates automatically to vendor/buyer (via email/SMS) when stage changes.

* Role-based access: The progressor user should have a slightly different UI (with tasks list and chain summary) than negotiator.
